# Architecture Boundaries

## Documentation Truth

- `docs/product/2026-03-20-jav-libary.md` describes both current product behavior and target architecture. Current code is the source of truth when documents conflict with implementation.
- In documents, clearly label current, target, and pending items.

## Implemented Current State

- Go HTTP backend, SQLite application database, scanning, scraping, task system, and REST API under `backend/` are implemented.
- The frontend can use real HTTP through `VITE_USE_WEB_API=true`.

## Desktop Shell Boundaries

- Electron now has an MVP shell under `electron/`: it starts or reuses the Go HTTP backend, waits for `/api/health`, starts or reuses Vite at `http://127.0.0.1:5173` in development, uses the Curated app icon and tray, loads the existing Web UI in BrowserWindow, and hides to tray when the window is closed. Packaged runtime still loads the backend-hosted static UI on `http://127.0.0.1:8081`.
- Electron preload/main process IPC remains deliberately narrow: current code exposes only `window.javLibrary.pickDirectory()` for native directory selection. Deep business IPC, mpv process control, and broader desktop file/permission bridges remain future desktop concerns unless current code proves otherwise.
- Vue renderer code must not assume Electron, mpv, PotPlayer, or any native-player executable exists.

## Frontend Business Code

- Rendering code depends on composables, frontend service contracts, and shared types.
- State management currently defaults to composables plus the service layer. Pinia or a similar store may be introduced incrementally for a small, bounded service or new feature when it clearly improves maintainability; avoid a big-bang migration or broad parallel global store.
- Views/components must not import concrete Web/Mock adapters directly for library behavior. Use `useLibraryService()` and add service-contract methods when a new capability is needed.
- Native-player handoff must stay optional and disabled by default when not configured. Express it through service settings and browser protocol templates, not hard-coded runtime assumptions.
- When adding a new capability, define DTOs/error codes/event names first, then wire the current HTTP adapter or a future stdio/IPC adapter behind the same service contract.
